text:
He got me to write this

I am a girl and football isn't supported in our country...

I loved football, supported Manchester since 2003 and Portugal since 2000 (due to Figo)

I became Ronaldo fan in 2006.... I was 13... When he was at real madrid I was 17....

That's where I got motivated by him that, I have to go out and do something for myself, something that I love....

I left my country in 20's, immigrated to Spain, got selected in different teams.. I can't continue that because of some injuries and medical problems... I was thinking to go back home and close the chapter

But again this guy stopped me from doing so, 2016 was the game when I saw him in Euros before saying good bye to my play.... And after ofcource I was influenced..

I Couldn't play, but decided to do some job in this field only....

Today I am happy to work as football technician (Jr analyst)....
Not only happy to earn money on my own, but the happiness is that I didn't give up, and doing what I want...

Just because of this man...
That's why no matter what he will always be my favorite player

text:
No disrespects to Ronaldo. I appreciate everything he had done for Man Utd before he left for Real Madrid. However I think Man Utd could have spent their money better this summer in signing a quality defensive midfielder. Furthermore they brought in Sancho (Don't even get me started) before him. Now this has created an inherent imbalance in the squad. It is simply overloaded with attacking minded players. 

We've got Ronaldo, Cavani, Sancho, Greenwood, Rashford, Martial, Amad and Elanga up front. Then we have Fernandes, Pogba, Van Der Beek, Lingard and Mata behind them. That's 13 freaking players. It is never in the game of Ronaldo (much like for example Berbatov) to track back the entire 90 mins of the game, every game.

As a fan of Man Utd since 1994, nothing hurts me more than watching the cycle of ups and downs since Fergie retired. Each time we seemed to have climbed 2 steps up, we suddenly dropped 3 steps backward. The defeat to Liverpool sucks, but it is necessary reality checker.

text:
This aged quickly. . . Ronaldo might be a special once a generation talent who works hard and has a winning mentality, however his presence completely destroyed any balance Man Utd had as a team. Why the balance is completely gone I can only speculate: it looks like the telepathic connection between Bruno and Pogba is now off with Ronaldo occupying the spaces that Bruno likes to run into, also looks like  a team that was never good at pressing is now woeful allowing opposition teams steady possession, the pressure to win from within and without is higher and youngesters (Rashford, Greenwood, Martial, Sancho) are all feeling it a bit too much. 

It may not be Ronaldo's fault but his signing set Man Utd back 2 years on the pitch. . . . unless off course their next manager has the kind of impact Tuchel did at Chelsea

text:
¬†@Minced Beef¬† I don't know what is going on in Woodward's or the board's head too. It is such a complete mess. We were suppose to build the next generation around Rashford, Greenwood and Martial. Yet they lost direction by bringing in Ronaldo who we all know, will never accept to starting on the bench occasionally.

Since the penalty loss against Villarreal, it was evident that Man Utd needed to strengthen 3 key positions. We needed a fox-in-the-box (who needed to be younger than Cavani), a solid center defender (sorry but Maguire and Lindel√∂f are B-rated players) and a tough defensive midfielder (ashamed that my namesake is a C-rated player).

What have we gotten? Only Varane. And then we get a mix of Sancho and Ronaldo. I don''t deny that Ronaldo is an ace scoring machine, but why do we need him when we have Cavani who is 2 years younger and is also much more of a team player? Someone like Harry Kane or Eerling Haaland would have been better choices.

text: I have followed football for over 50 years, playing, watching, immersing myself in the game. I have seen many superstars over the years which don‚Äôt need naming. Cristiano is one in a million. He came from a very poor background in Madeira and has never forgotten that. He is humble, amiable, can converse in a few languages and of course a very rich man. He is an absolutely exceptional football player with an amazing dedication and work rate. However he cannot enjoy life outside his front door like normal people. He can‚Äôt just go for a walk in public or go for meal say without someone wanting him to share his time with them‚Ä¶with selfies, questions etc. Its human nature to worship people like him. His life is centred around his training at his club and his public appearances are more or less limited to 90 odd minutes once or twice a week. For this he gets paid a lot of money. When he retires, for a good few years, he is still not going to be able to live a normal life‚Ä¶.whatever he does. But he is dedicated. And he deserves everything he gets. He is a good man and I feel honoured to watch him play. Even when he contributes to his team beating mine. Because I am a football supporter. People will always hate. That‚Äôs where we are. But this guy stands head and shoulders above many. And I wish him a long and happy life. üëå

text:
¬†@Bodhi Martin¬† as some who IS a surgeon, I agree. It‚Äôs definitely harder to become a top footballer than a surgeon. There are 2000 consultant general surgeons in the UK, before you consider all the other surgical specialities. 
1.9 million adults play football twice a week, 45% of 11-15 year old boys do to. 
There are around 600 players in the premier league each year. How many are ‚ÄúTOP‚Äù? 
By the time you reach the level of being considered a top player, maybe top 100 in your position in the world, the numbers are staggering.

So yes, it is harder to be a top footballer than a surgeon. Whether Ronaldo could be a surgeon is irrelevant, I know damn well I couldn‚Äôt be a top footballer!

If by harder you mean hours worked etc then it‚Äôs hard to tell. I‚Äôve been training for 19 years, doing an average 60 hour week at work, and 10 in extra stuff at home (studying, writing papers etc) The most I‚Äôve ever done is 127 hours in one week. I assume Ronaldo doesn‚Äôt do that!

text:
What Cristiano Ronaldo has meant for me:

I was an obese blobber of fat 5 years ago, I weighed 127KG and I'm just 174cm in height. 

I had already been following Cristiano Ronaldo for years at that stage, but during his Euro 2016 performances, every time he performed to his utter best (which was nearly every game at Euro 2016 as he was so vital with his goals, assists and leadership), I started thinking "What if I could use the same kind of focus Cristiano Ronaldo has on performing on the pitch every single day, on losing weight?". And I thought if I would set a goal of doing x amount of workout training per day and a weight loss goal with the same kind of focus this guy puts into his football, I would lose weight and I would finally be successful in that, after failing multiple diets.

And so the day Portugal won the Euro's in 2016 was the day I ordered my treadmill and my journey had begun. 3 months later I was down to 108KG, by the end of 2016 I was down to 98KG. Today I'm at 73KG and I swear that without Cristiano Ronaldo being my role model, I wouldn't have achieved this. And most people who are obese like I was will know, you are depressed being that fat, you lose confidence in everything you do. It's only the sight of you and the physical pain of being so fat, it's also mentally exhausting.
author: Anthony Anthony

author: Crius XI

text: ¬†@Crius XI¬† right on, this is the argument everyone makes about ronaldo. The man has goals. Except, modern High pressing tactical systems (employed by the likes of pep, poch, klopp and tuchel) are system centric. They don't have a place for players like messi, Neymar or Ronaldo. a good example of this is Juve and Sarri/Pirlo. If you go look at Juventus's shot maps and patterns of play during the years Ronaldo was there, you can see that the productivity of players around him drastically decreases and Ronaldo takes an insane amount of shots with his shot conversion rate being low. The answer to to ronaldo taking a lot of shots and basically sucking up all the oxygen in the forward department is to specifically build a team to compensate for his weaknesses. The older Ronaldo gets, and the less versatile he gets, this becomes much harder. This is what we see in Juventus, where systemically sound teams are able to beat Juventus (who rely on Ronaldo half heartedly and are unable to have a pressing system) in the champions league. The era for a player like Ronaldo is simply gone. The cost of his high goals is the loss of the system and goals from other facets of the team. A good manager like Tuchel or klopp can solve for Ronaldo's weaknesses like they do with Jorginho/Trent but someone like Ole/Allegri/Pirlo can't do the same.
author: dhruv holla

text: ¬†@Crius XI¬† you're considering Ronaldo is a vaccum. The fact of the matter is that the man has an impact on how the entire team play and serve him the ball. If you build a team around Ronaldo and negate him, your team fails. Sancho hasn't been able to hit his peak because the quality of service and passing opportunities he's getting are much lower than in Dortmund. Greenwood plays well because he passes to ronaldo the least. Cavani has great work rate and links up play much better than Ronaldo as well. These players form a better Utd side than one with ronaldo in it. Sure you can put Cavani and Ronaldo together, but the entire system suffers because of it. Ole seems good at playing a counter attacking system or quick movement system which he won't do with 2 old guys up front. Who's crossing the ball? The team doesn't even have a solid defensive midfield and if their entire midfield is pressing then the defense gets exposed more.
author: dhruv holla

text: ¬†@Crius XI¬† my point is that Ronaldo isn‚Äôt a great dribbler anymore. You can see this when he plays and it‚Äôs also backed up by stats.
